,"modUser":"dotcms.org.1","working":true,"titleImage":{"present":false},"htmlpage":false,"fileAsset":false,"vanityUrl":false,"keyValue":false,"archived":false,"live":true},"template":{"iDate":1543427392897,"type":"template","owner":"","inode":"888fe5c0-98e3-4ff8-80f9-a61be97a1e5d","identifier":"e357b275-3cc8-455b-b7d7-0adaefb51040","source":"DB","title":"anonymous_layout_1582562696562","friendlyName":"","modDate":1582562696588,"modUser":"dotcms.org.1","sortOrder":0,"showOnMenu":false,"image":"","drawed":true,"drawedBody":"{\"header\":true,\"footer\":true,\"body\":{\"rows\":[{\"columns\":[{\"containers\":[{\"identifier\":\"/application/containers/default/\",\"uuid\":\"1\"}],\"widthPercent\":83,\"leftOffset\":2,\"preview\":false,\"width\":10,\"left\":1}],\"styleClass\":\"section-md\"}]},\"sidebar\":{\"containers\":[],\"location\":\"\",\"width\":\"small\",\"widthPercent\":20,\"preview\":false}}","theme":"d7b0ebc2-37ca-4a5a-b769-e8a3ff187661","anonymous":true,"template":false,"locked":false,"versionId":"e357b275-3cc8-455b-b7d7-0adaefb51040","versionType":"template","deleted":false,"working":true,"permissionId":"e357b275-3cc8-455b-b7d7-0adaefb51040","archived":false,"name":"anonymous_layout_1582562696562","live":false,"permissionType":"com.dotmarketing.portlets.templates.model.Template","new":false,"categoryId":"888fe5c0-98e3-4ff8-80f9-a61be97a1e5d","idate":1543427392897,"canEdit":true},"urlContentMap":{"postingDate":1563310500000,"body":"<p>A family ski trip can be a bonding, exhilarating experience. There&rsquo;s something mind clearing about ascending up the mountain bundled up in the crisp air, and then soaring down the snow covered slopes on skis. But keeping warm and comfortable is key to the fun. And, the secret to keeping warm is making sure you have the all important ski equipment. Mountain TravelingMom shares her secrets to making your ski vacation a success for the entire family, including a free printable ski trip packing list.</p>\n<h2>Ski Trip Packing List: Everything You Need for a Family Ski Vacation</h2>\n<p>If I left it up to my kids they would arrive at our vacation destination with a suitcase full of toys and nothing else. Thus I become chief travel packer. Whether you wanted that job, chances are you&rsquo;re the one who takes on the responsibility for packing when it&rsquo;s vacation time. When you add up ski gear for each person in the family, it is quite a ski trip packing list!</p>\n<p>Once you&rsquo;ve decided on your family-friendly ski destination, booked your ski lodging, ski passes and arranged for your ski rentals its time to make an all-important packing list. We share our complete list as well as tips on special items to ensure your family ski vacation is a success. Download our Ultimate Family Ski Trip Packing List to make sure you don&rsquo;t forget anything important.</p>\n<h2>Comprehensive Ski Trip Packing List</h2>\n<p><strong>Travel Documents &amp; Misc Travel Essentials</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>I.D.</li>\n<li>Confirmation Numbers/ Itinerary</li>\n<li>Credit Cards</li>\n<li>Health Insurance Cards</li>\n<li>Travel Insurance Documents</li>\n<li>Ski Passes (Make sure to purchase in advance!)</li>\n<li>Auto Insurance Cards</li>\n<li>Toys, books or games</li>\n<li>Fully charged electronics</li>\n<li>Charging cords</li>\n<li>Camera/ Phone</li>\n<li>Snacks</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Ski Gear to Pack</h2>\n<p>Bringing the right ski gear will make your family ski vacation a success. Helmets may be the most important piece of ski gear. Not only does a helmet keep your head safe, but also warm. We like POC helmets for the kids and Smith helmets or K2 helmets for the adults. Ski gloves made of Gortex will keep fingers dry and warm. Our favorites are Swany and Hestra. A good pair of goggles will make all the difference on a powder day, or a day with flat light. Thermal under layers should be a moisture wick fabric, not cotton. Multiple pairs of socks made for skiing are a must. Invest in a few pairs of SmartWool ski socks or Stance ski socks. Warm, but not sweaty feet will keep you happy.</p>\n<p>Ski resorts are located at high altitude and drinking plenty of water is key to preventing altitude sickness. So, you may want to bring a Camelbak hydration system or whatever it is that gets your family to drink water.</p>\n<p>Cold drains cell phone batteries, so you will want to pack a pocket charger to make sure that you can stay connected while on the mountain. Pocket warmers next to your cell phone can also help, as well as keep you a bit warmer.</p>\n<p>Don&rsquo;t forget candy to carry in your pockets to give the kids energy, or to use as an extra incentive while skiing.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Helmet</li>\n<li>Goggles</li>\n<li>Neck Gaiter</li>\n<li>Ski pants and ski jacket</li>\n<li>Thermal under layers</li>\n<li>Ski gloves</li>\n<li>Hand/ foot warmers</li>\n<li>Ski socks</li>\n<li>Hydration pack (Camelbak)</li>\n<li>Pocket cell phone charger</li>\n<li>Pocket candy/ treats</li>\n<li>Ski boots*</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Clothing to Pack</h2>\n<p>Layers, fleece, moisture wick under layers and warm, non-slip snow boots will be your most important pieces of non-ski clothing. The sun is bright at altitude so make sure to pack sunglasses. And, don&rsquo;t forget a swimsuit! There&rsquo;s nothing better than relaxing in a hot tub surrounded by snow after an exhilarating day on the ski slopes.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Warm pants and shirts</li>\n<li>Sweaters</li>\n<li>Jeans</li>\n<li>Snow boots</li>\n<li>Wool socks</li>\n<li>Warm hat</li>\n<li>Fleece jacket</li>\n<li>Warm Vest</li>\n<li>Gloves</li>\n<li>Scarf</li>\n<li>Dinner/ Evening Clothing</li>\n<li>Swim Suit</li>\n<li>Sunglasses</li>\n<li>Undergarments</li>\n<li>Sleepwear</li>\n<li>Exercise Clothing</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Medicine / Toiletries to Pack</h2>\n<p>While it is always a good idea to bring along some kind of headache medicine, it is an important precaution while on a ski trip. A headache will be the first sign of altitude sickness. Drink plenty of water. Read tips on preventing altitude sickness. Also pain relievers can also help relieve sore muscles.</p>\n<p>Ski resorts are also located in dry climates. A saline nose spray can help prevent bloody noses from the dry climate.</p>\n<p>Gold Bond powder sprinkled on the feet will help keep ski socks dry, and warm.</p>\n<h2>Ski Equipment to Rent</h2>\n<p>We live in a ski resort town and so do own our own ski equipment. However, with the cost of transporting skis on airlines, you are going to be better off renting your skis or snowboards. If you ski several times per year, I would recommend investing in and bringing your own ski or snowboard boots. But I still think you will be better off renting skis. Plus it is a fun opportunity to try different types of skis for different snow conditions. Check to see if your ski rental company or hotel will provide ski valet service.</p>\n<p>As you can see, a family ski trip requires a lot of gear. Use this comprehensive ski trip packing list to ensure you don&rsquo;t forget anything important. For more family ski trip tips click over to Mountain TravelingMom&rsquo;s articles on tips for choosing a family-friendly ski resort, tips for a first family ski vacation and where in Colorado to find affordable ski lessons.</p>","inode":"6b7b8db9-f95f-4514-98b4-5dcf44ec7862","host":"48190c8c-42c4-46af-8d1a-0cd5db894797","locked":false,"stInode":"799f176a-d32e-4844-a07c-1b5fcd107578","contentType":"Blog","identifier":"3d6fa2a4-2b48-4421-a2f5-b6518a7c0830","image":"/data/shared/assets/6/b/6b7b8db9-f95f-4514-98b4-5dcf44ec7862/image/ski-trip-packing-list.jpg","urlTitle":"the-ultimate-family-ski-trip-packing-list","tags":"skiing,family,vaction","folder":"SYSTEM_FOLDER","hasTitleImage":true,"sortOrder":0,"hostName":"demo.dotcms.com","modDate":1586206784501,"title":"The Ultimate Family Ski Trip Packing List","baseType":"CONTENT","archived":false,"working":true,"live":true,"owner":"dotcms.org.1","languageId":1,"URL_MAP_FOR_CONTENT":"/blog/post/the-u